Moderate vs. Large Number of Devices. FedDyn significantly outperforms competing methods in the practically relevant massively distributed scenario.
We report the performance of FedDyn on CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 with moderate and large number of devices in Table 1, while keeping the participation level constant (10%)percent10(10\%) and the data amounts balanced. Specifically, the moderately distributed setting has 100100100 devices with 500500500 images per device. The massively distributed setting has 100010001000 devices with 505050 images per device for CIFAR-10, as well as 500500500 devices with 100100100 images per device for CIFAR-100. In each distributed setting, the data is partitioned in both IID and non-IID (Dirichlet 0.3) fashion. FedDyn leads to substantial transmission reduction in each of the regimes.

Full vs. Partial Participation Levels. FedDyn outperforms baseline methods across different device participation levels. We consider different device participation levels with 100100100 devices and balanced data in Table 2 where part of CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 results are omitted since they are reported in moderate number of devices section of Table 1. The Shakespeare non-IID results are separately shown, since it has a natural non-IID split which does not conform with the Dirichlet distribution. The communication gain, with respect to best baseline, increases with greater participation levels from 2.9×2.9\times to 9.4×9.4\times; 4.0×4.0\times to 12.8×12.8\times and 4.2×4.2\times to 7.9×7.9\times for CIFAR-10 in different device distribution settings. We observe a similar performance increase in full participation for most of the datasets. This validates our hypothesis that FedDyn more efficiently incorporates information from all devices compared to other methods, and results in more savings in full participation. Similar to previous results, a greater target accuracy gives a greater savings in most of the settings. We also report results for 1%percent11\% participation regime with different device distribution settings (See Table 5 in Appendix A.1).

IID vs. non-IID Device Distribution. FedDyn outperforms baseline methods across different device distribution levels. We consider heterogeneous device distributions in the context of varying device numbers, participation levels and balanced-unbalanced settings in Table 1, 2 and 4 (Appendix A.1) respectively. Device distributions become more non-IID as we go from IID, Dirichlet .6.6.6 to Dirichlet .3.3.3 splits which makes global optimization problem harder. We see a clear effect of this change in Table 2 for 10%percent1010\% participation level and in Table 4 for unbalanced setting. For instance, increasing non-IID level results in a greater communication saving such as from 2.9×2.9\times, 4.0×4.0\times to 4.2×4.2\times in CIFAR-10 10%percent1010\% participation. Similar statement holds for MNIST, EMNIST-L and Shakespeare in Table 2 and for CIFAR-10 unbalanced setting in Table 4. We do not observe a significant difference in savings for full participation setting in Table 2.
